        <bioghist id="ref5">
            <head>Historical/Biographical Note</head>
            <p>Carl Reeve (1900-1980), a son, along with Harold Ware, of Ella Reeve Bloor (1862-1951) was a Communist, the chair of the Washington State CP, at one time served on the Central Committee of the CPUSA, was Educational Director of Party's Eastern Pennsylvania organization, and was in 1940 a Communist candiate for Senator from Pennsylvania. He wrote 
                <emph render="italic">The Life and Times of Daniel De Leon</emph> (1972) and with his wife Ann Barton Reeve, 
                <emph render="italic">James Connolly and the United States: The Road to the Irish Rebellion</emph> (1978).</p>
        </bioghist>
        <scopecontent id="ref3">
            <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
            <p>The collection contains research materials, notes and reviews pertaining to 
                <emph render="italic">James Connolly and the United States</emph>, correspondence of Ann and Carl Reeve, manuscripts my Ann and Carl Reeve, including a review essay by the latter "Under Which Flage: A Play by James Connolly," two small Irish nationalist posters, one memorializing Connolly, the other in Gaelic, a file on the Transport Workers Union of America, Local 100 (New York City), and a fragile copy of the 
                <emph render="italic">Sinn Fein Rebellion Handbook: Easter, 1916</emph>, compiled and published by the Weekly Irish Times of Dublin, Ireland.</p>
        </scopecontent>
        <acqinfo id="ref22">
            <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition note</head>
            <p>Susan Reeve Steinmann sent a gift of Carl Reeve's papers in 2005. The accession number associated with this gift is 2005.020.</p>
        </acqinfo>
        <userestrict id="ref23">
            <head>Use Restrictions</head>
            <p>Any rights (including copyright and related rights to publicity and privacy) held by Susan Reeve Steinmann, Carl Reeve's heir, were transferred to New York University in 2005. Permission to publish or reproduce materials in this collection must be secured from the Tamiment Library.</p>
        </userestrict>
        <accessrestrict id="ref24">
            <head>Access Restrictions</head>
            <p>Open for research without restrictions.</p>
        </accessrestrict>
